{"id": 100629, "acmi_id": "", "title": "Storyboarding in Isle of Dogs", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "storyboarding-in-isle-of-dogs", "creator_credit": "Wes Anderson", "credit_line": "<p>Courtesy Searchlight Pictures</p>", "headline_credit": "United States, 2018", "record_type": "group", "type": "Object", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2023-02-09", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "first_production_date": "2018-01-01T11:00:00+11:00", "brief_description": "<p>Isle of Dogs (2018) is a stop-motion film, set in a retro-futuristic Japan, that follows a gang of dogs exiled from Megasaki City to Trash Island, where they help a young boy track down his lost dog.  </p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 87, "name": "Storyboards to Academy Awards", "description": "Storyboards allow filmmakers, showrunners and game designers to visualise and communicate how their stories will look on-screen."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Isle of Dogs</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Wes Anderson</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>United States, 2018</p>", "description": "<p><i>Isle of Dogs</i> (2018) is a stop-motion film, set in a retro-futuristic Japan, that follows a gang of dogs exiled from Megasaki City to Trash Island, where they help a young boy track down his lost dog.  </p>\n<p>After the story was scripted, director Wes Anderson sketched each shot on loose paper, referencing Japanese filmmaker Akira Kurosawa’s <i>Seven Samurai</i> (1954) and <i>Yojimbo</i> (1961), as well as Utagawa Hiroshige’s woodblock prints (in the ukiyo-e style), which storyboard artist Jay Clarke found naturally represented camera movements and merged into the storyboard style.   </p>\n<p>Clarke’s storyboards were then turned into a basic animation to help determine the rhythm of scenes, which guided the hundreds of animators who brought the st